# <%= current_page.data.title %>

This runbook covers VM restore from Azure Recovery Services Vault (RSV) for Heritage VMs. It defines which restore method to use for each incident scenario and provides step-by-step CLI commands.

For cross-subscription restore precedent see the [Atlassian Staging Build runbook](../Services/atlassian-staging-build.html).

---

## Scenario → Method quick reference

| Scenario | Use method | Why |
|----------|-----------|-----|
| **S1** — Data corruption / ransomware (VM still running) | **D — File Recovery (ILR)** | Zero downtime on source; fastest path; no new Azure resources |
| **S2** — VM non-bootable (OS failure, bad patch) | **C — Replace Existing** | Preserves VM identity: NIC, IP, RBAC. Planned downtime only |
| **S3** — VM deleted (accidental or malicious) | **A — Create New VM** | Source gone; simplest single-command restore |
| **S4** — Clone for staging / DR drill / cross-subscription | **B — Restore Managed Disks** | Cross-subscription; ARM template allows full config control. Atlassian precedent |
| **S5** — Single file or config loss | **D — File Recovery (ILR)** | Fastest path; no full restore warranted |

> **Method A/B fallback:** If Method A fails due to SKU unavailability, fall back to Method B immediately using the ARM template generated by the failed restore job.
> 
> **ADE-encrypted VMs:** ILR (Method D) and Replace Existing (Method C) are not supported. Use Method A or B, then manually extract files post-restore if needed.

