## Prerequisites

### 1. RBAC — minimum roles required

| Method | Role | Scope |
|--------|------|-------|
| All | `Backup Operator` | Recovery Services Vault |
| A — Create New VM | `Virtual Machine Contributor` | Target resource group |
| A — Create New VM | `Network Contributor` | Target VNet/subnet resource group |
| B — Restore Managed Disks | `Storage Account Contributor` | Staging storage account |
| B — Restore Managed Disks | `Virtual Machine Contributor` | Target resource group |
| B — Restore Managed Disks | `Network Contributor` | Target VNet/subnet resource group |
| C — Replace Existing | `Virtual Machine Contributor` | Source resource group |
| C — Replace Existing (vault-tier) | `Storage Account Contributor` | Staging storage account |
| D — File Recovery | `Backup Operator` | Recovery Services Vault |

### 2. Verify cross-subscription restore (CSR) state — required for Method B

Methods A and B support cross-subscription vault-tier restore only if CSR is enabled on the vault. Check before attempting a cross-subscription restore:

```bash
az backup vault show \
  --name <vault-name> \
  --resource-group <vault-rg> \
  --subscription <source-sub-id> \
  --query "properties.crossSubscriptionRestoreState" -o tsv
```

Expected output: `Enabled`. If the output is `Disabled` or `PermanentlyDisabled`, raise a platform ticket — `PermanentlyDisabled` is irreversible and the vault will need to be replaced.

For a full pre-flight check across all Heritage vaults, run `rsv-csr-check.sh` from the workspace root.

### 3. Recovery point tiers

With the agreed 4-hour Enhanced V2 policy, every VM produces two recovery point tiers:

| Tier | Retention | Restore speed | Cross-sub? |
|------|-----------|---------------|------------|
| **Snapshot (Instant Restore)** | 7 days | Minutes–15 min | Same subscription only |
| **Vault-Standard** | 56 days daily / 8 weeks / 2 months / 1 year | 30–90 min | Cross-sub with CSR enabled |

Always prefer the snapshot-tier recovery point (within 7 days) for the fastest RTO.

### 4. Environment shuttering (production restores)

Dependent services must be stopped or isolated **before** triggering a restore on any production VM. Crime validated this during a PostgreSQL Flexible Server restore — leaving services running while restoring caused state inconsistency.

Confirm with the service owner which upstream/downstream services need shuttering. If no shuttering documentation exists for the target VM, treat this as a gap and raise it before proceeding.

### 5. Find your vault, container, and recovery point

```bash
VaultName="<vault-name>"
VaultRG="<vault-resource-group>"
SourceSubscription="<source-sub-id>"
ItemName="<vm-hostname>"  # e.g. POAG-WEB-VM01

az account set --subscription $SourceSubscription

# List vaults if unknown
az backup vault list --output table

# Find the container name for your VM
ContainerName=$(az backup container list \
  --resource-group $VaultRG \
  --vault-name $VaultName \
  --backup-management-type AzureIaasVM \
  --query "[?properties.friendlyName=='$ItemName'].name" -o tsv | head -n 1)

echo "Container: $ContainerName"

# List available recovery points (latest first)
az backup recoverypoint list \
  --vault-name $VaultName \
  --resource-group $VaultRG \
  --container-name $ContainerName \
  --item-name $ItemName \
  --query '[].{Name:name, Time:properties.recoveryPointTime, Tier:properties.recoveryPointTierDetails[0].type}' \
  -o table

# Select recovery point — usually the most recent
RecoveryPointName=$(az backup recoverypoint list \
  --vault-name $VaultName \
  --resource-group $VaultRG \
  --container-name $ContainerName \
  --item-name $ItemName \
  --query '[0].name' -o tsv)

echo "Recovery point: $RecoveryPointName"
```

