## Method C — Replace Existing (In-Place)

**Use for: S2 (VM non-bootable — OS failure, bad patch)**

Replaces the disks on the existing VM with the selected recovery point. VM identity is fully preserved: NIC, IP address, RBAC assignments. Azure takes a safety snapshot of the current VM state before replacing.

> **Planned downtime mandatory** — the VM must be deallocated before the restore job completes.  
> **Same subscription only** — cross-subscription not supported.  
> **ADE / CMK encrypted VMs:** not supported — use Method A.  
> **Vault-tier:** the `Transfer Data to Vault` sub-task must show `Completed` on the recovery point. If it shows `Not started`, use Method A instead.

### Step 1 — Deallocate the VM

```bash
SourceSubscription="<source-sub-id>"
SourceRG="<vm-resource-group>"
VMName="<vm-name>"

az account set --subscription $SourceSubscription

az vm deallocate \
  --resource-group $SourceRG \
  --name $VMName
```

Wait for the deallocation to complete before proceeding.

### Step 2 — Restore to original location

```bash
VaultName="<vault-name>"
VaultRG="<vault-resource-group>"
ContainerName="<container-name>"  # from Prerequisites step 4
ItemName="<vm-hostname>"
RecoveryPointName="<recovery-point-name>"

# For vault-tier recovery points only — staging storage account must be in same region as vault:
StorageAccountName="<staging-storage-account-name>"
StorageAccountRG="<storage-account-rg>"

az backup restore restore-disks \
  --resource-group $VaultRG \
  --vault-name $VaultName \
  --container-name $ContainerName \
  --item-name $ItemName \
  --rp-name $RecoveryPointName \
  --restore-mode OriginalLocation \
  --storage-account $StorageAccountName \
  --storage-account-resource-group $StorageAccountRG
```

> For snapshot-tier recovery points (≤ 7 days), `--storage-account` is not required.

Monitor the restore job in the Azure Portal: vault → Backup Jobs. Look for the job status to change to `Completed`.

### Step 3 — Start the VM and verify

```bash
az vm start \
  --resource-group $SourceRG \
  --name $VMName \
  --subscription $SourceSubscription
```

SSH in and verify services are running. Check the application logs.

> **Run Command replay:** The Azure VM agent replays the last `az vm run-command invoke` on boot. If Run Command was used before the restore, be aware the previous command will execute again on startup.

The safety snapshot Azure took before the replace is visible in the VM's disk snapshot list — delete it once you have confirmed the restore is successful. The original OS disk AND any attached data disk(s) are also retained in the resource group — delete them after verification to avoid orphaned resource cost.

