## Method A — Create New VM

**Use for: S3 (VM deleted)**

Provisions a brand-new VM from the selected recovery point. The original VM does not need to exist. Non-destructive.

> **Post-restore:** The new VM gets a dynamic IP — re-apply any static IP manually. RBAC role assignments scoped to the original VM are not carried over — reassign them. Extensions are installed but not enabled — reinstall if needed.  
> **VM SKU:** Matches the recovery point SKU, not any post-backup resize.  
> **Complex network config** (multiple NICs, load balancer, reserved IPs): use Method B instead.  
> **ADE-encrypted VMs:** supported (full restore only).

```bash
VaultName="<vault-name>"
VaultRG="<vault-resource-group>"
SourceSubscription="<source-sub-id>"
ContainerName="<container-name>"  # from Prerequisites step 4
ItemName="<vm-hostname>"
RecoveryPointName="<recovery-point-name>"

TargetRG="<target-resource-group>"
TargetVMName="<new-vm-name>"
TargetVNet="<target-vnet-name>"
TargetSubnet="<target-subnet-name>"
TargetVNetRG="<target-vnet-resource-group>"
StorageAccountName="<staging-storage-account-name>"

az account set --subscription $SourceSubscription

az backup restore restore-disks \
  --resource-group $VaultRG \
  --vault-name $VaultName \
  --container-name $ContainerName \
  --item-name $ItemName \
  --rp-name $RecoveryPointName \
  --restore-mode AlternateLocation \
  --target-resource-group $TargetRG \
  --target-vm-name $TargetVMName \
  --target-vnet-name $TargetVNet \
  --target-subnet-name $TargetSubnet \
  --target-vnet-resource-group $TargetVNetRG \
  --storage-account $StorageAccountName
```

Monitor progress in the Azure Portal: vault → Backup Jobs. Typical RTO from snapshot-tier: 15–30 min. From vault-tier: 30–90 min. VMs > 1 TB may exceed the 4-hour RTO target — no Azure SLA exists for large VMs.

